INSERT INTO posts (id, title, slug, excerpt, content, cover_image_url, is_published, is_gated, published_at, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (2, 'NA', 'na', 'na', '<p>If you self-manage rental properties in Philadelphia, you already know the math gets complicated fast. What should you charge for rent next year? Is your property actually cash flowing after all the expenses? Can your prospective tenant realistically afford the unit? When your lease is up, how much is too much to raise rent without losing a good tenant?</p><p>Most landlords guess. The good ones calculate.</p><p>After talking to dozens of small landlords across Philadelphia — from West Philly to Kensington to South Philly to Germantown — the same problem kept coming up. Landlords were making major financial decisions based on gut feel, not numbers. One landlord told me he had been undercharging rent by $300 a month for two years because he never checked the market. That is $7,200 he left on the table.</p><p>We built four free tools at Oakwood specifically for self-managing landlords in Philadelphia. No account required. No credit card. Just go to <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 underline hover:no-underline" href="https://oakwoodpropertysolutions.com/tools">oakwoodpropertysolutions.com/tools</a> and start running the numbers.</p><h2><strong>1. Cash Flow Calculator</strong></h2><p>This is the one every landlord needs before making any decision about their property. Most landlords know their monthly rent. Very few know their actual monthly cash flow after factoring in mortgage, taxes, insurance, maintenance reserves, vacancy, and property management costs.</p><p>The cash flow calculator walks you through every line item and tells you exactly where you stand. If the number is negative, you need to know that now — not after your next repair bill wipes out two months of rent.</p><p>Use it when you are evaluating whether to hold or sell a property, deciding whether a rent increase makes sense, or trying to figure out why your rental feels like it is not making money even though your unit is occupied.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 underline hover:no-underline" href="https://oakwoodpropertysolutions.com/tools">Try the Cash Flow Calculator</a></p><h2><strong>2. ROI Calculator</strong></h2><p>Occupancy is not the same as performance. A fully occupied unit can still be a bad investment if you overpaid for the property or your expenses are eating the rent.</p><p>The ROI calculator factors in your purchase price, down payment, closing costs, annual rent collected, and annual operating expenses to give you your actual cash-on-cash return. This is the number that tells you whether your rental property is outperforming, matching, or underperforming what you could earn putting that same capital elsewhere.</p><p>Use it once a year as a performance review for your property. If your ROI is under 5 percent, you have a decision to make.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 underline hover:no-underline" href="https://oakwoodpropertysolutions.com/tools">Try the ROI Calculator</a></p><h2><strong>3. Rent Affordability Calculator</strong></h2><p>Before you place a tenant, you need to know whether they can actually afford the unit. The industry standard is that rent should not exceed 30 percent of a tenant''s gross monthly income. That means a tenant needs to earn at least $3,333 per month to comfortably afford a $1,000 per month apartment.</p><p>The affordability calculator runs that math instantly. Plug in the rent and it tells you the minimum monthly income your applicant needs. Use it early in the screening process before you spend money on a background check on someone who cannot qualify.</p><p>This matters more in Philadelphia than people realize. With rising rents across the city, tenant income qualification is one of the top reasons landlords end up with late payments and eviction proceedings. Screen smarter upfront and you will avoid a lot of headaches on the back end.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 underline hover:no-underline" href="https://oakwoodpropertysolutions.com/tools">Try the Rent Affordability Calculator</a></p><h2><strong>4. Lease Renewal Calculator</strong></h2><h1>This is the most underrated tool we built. When your lease comes up for renewal, the decision of how much to raise rent is one of the most consequential financial decisions you make as a landlord — and most people just pick a number and hope the tenant stays.</h1><p></p>', NULL, 'f', 'f', '2026-03-25 22:10:25.799', '2026-03-25 22:10:25.595105', '2026-04-03 00:53:40.016');
